<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1921-03-28T23:59:59-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1921-03-28T00:00:00-05:00" n="388" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d388">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">893.74/102: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">Messrs. <gloss type="from">J. P. Morgan &amp;
                                    Company</gloss> to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                    State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">New
                                        York</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1921-03-28"><hi rend="italic">March 28,
                                1921</hi></date>.<lb/>[Received March 28—2:41
                            p.m.]</dateline></opener>
                        <p>Attention of Mr. MacMurray.<note n="28" xml:id="d388fn28">John Van A.
                                MacMurray, Chief, Division of Far Eastern Affairs, Department of
                                State.</note> We can now confirm that British, French and Japanese,
                            as well as American, groups of Chinese consortium are not interested in
                            financing Federal Telegraph Company contract.</p>
                        <closer><hi rend="smallcaps">J. P. Morgan &amp; Company</hi></closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>